  "opinion": "As a 77-year-old retired woman living in Lecce, I approach social media with a mix of curiosity and caution, given my limited but regular use a few times monthly. My perspective on managing fake content is shaped by a lifetime of experiences, from growing up with a parent who had a PhD and another with no formal education, which taught me to value both education and practical wisdom. Being an atheist, I rely on evidence and critical thinking rather than faith when navigating online information. My high neuroticism makes me naturally wary and anxious about misinformation, especially as I see how quickly falsehoods can spread and harm communities, while my moderate openness allows me to explore new ideas without being easily swayed. To deal with fake content, I start by verifying sources before sharing anything; I often check with trusted news outlets or fact-checking websites, a habit that stems from my curious nature and lower secondary education, which emphasized basic literacy and skepticism. I also engage in discussions with friends and family, using my high extraversion to connect and spread awareness about spotting fake news, though my moderate agreeableness means I don't shy away from challenging dubious claims. In my hobbies like hiking and yoga, I've learned patience and mindfulness, which I apply online by taking a moment to reflect before reacting to sensational posts. Living as a native-born Italian in a small city, I've seen how local gossip can mirror online rumors, so I prioritize community trust over viral trends. Ultimately, I believe that personal responsibility, combined with digital literacy efforts, is key to combating fake content, and I encourage others to stay informed and question everything, just as I do in my daily life.",
